  ('9623bacb-3042-5fc4-ad31-38234851a1d4', '3385d4a5-b4c2-5331-a7a9-53a03f3f4869', '2ee55359-b5ce-5fa2-8710-cb048521502a', '100002785402', 'Section 1 Health journal: Why Steady-State Cardio and Cross-Training for Your Health and Wellbeing Many people struggle to make time for exercise. Today’s fast pace, busy schedules, and long to-do lists often push physical activity to the bottom of our priorities. In my view, the belief that exercise requires hours at the gym discourages many people from starting, as does the idea that a personal trainer is essential. In reality, staying active does not need to take over our days to be effective. Some people prefer steady-state cardio, such as jogging, cycling, or using an exercise bike at a comfortable, continuous pace. Others enjoy cross-training, which combines short, structured workouts that can be completed in under an hour. Both approaches show that exercise can fit into everyday life without being overwhelming. 2 Regular exercise plays a key role in keeping us strong and resilient. Steady-state cardio supports heart and lung health by keeping the heart rate elevated for longer periods, improving circulation and endurance. Cross-training, on the other hand, combines cardio with strength and functional movements, helping to build muscle while also improving stamina and balance. These forms of exercise help manage weight, support posture, and increase overall physical confidence. Over time, they reduce the risk of long-term conditions such as high blood pressure or type 2 diabetes, a link supported by many long-term health studies. Health experts often suggest around 30 minutes of moderate exercise on most days, which shows that consistency is often more important than extreme intensity. 3 <p data-ccp-props="{&quot;33555155', 'Reading comprehension', 'Synthesising and critically engaging with text', 'D2', 1, 'active'),
  ('402ddc0f-9a6c-56ec-b942-68b35ac37fbf', '3385d4a5-b4c2-5331-a7a9-53a03f3f4869', '2ee55359-b5ce-5fa2-8710-cb048521502a', '100002785403', 'Section 1 Posting - Volunteer Opportunity: After School Community Learning Programme Are you interested in supporting young learners while gaining useful experience? Volunteers are invited to join the After School Community Learning Programme, which supports students aged 8–12 as they explore specialised subjects in a safe and welcoming environment. Before beginning, volunteers attend an introductory session where they learn about programme routines, available materials, safety procedures, and expectations from experienced staff. This session helps volunteers understand how lessons are organised and what support is provided so they feel prepared. After the session, volunteers select their preferred subject and arrange their schedule through a form. All necessary supplies are provided. 2 The After School Community Learning Programme is ideal for volunteers who want to develop leadership and communication skills while working directly with children. Another initiative, the School Peer Observation Programme, takes a different approach. In that programme, participants attend lessons, complete observation checklists, and discuss teaching strategies during meetings to reflect on their experience, but they do not usually interact with students. In contrast, the After School Community Learning Programme offers an active teaching environment. Volunteers support small groups, guide students through learning tasks, and help them practise study routines during scheduled sessions. They also encourage focus and positive behaviour, contributing to an organised and supportive space. These regular interactions build students’ confidence and allow volunteers to contribute meaningfully to their community, which many previous volunteers have found rewarding. <p data-ccp-props="{&quot;335551550&quot;:1,&quot;335551620&quot;:1,&quot;335559683&quot;:0,&quot;335562764&quot;:2,&quot;33556', 'Reading comprehension', 'Understanding meaning', 'D2', 1, 'active'),
