  ('76553582-3b27-54ab-bd1b-13459d6f6ddc', '3385d4a5-b4c2-5331-a7a9-53a03f3f4869', '2ee55359-b5ce-5fa2-8710-cb048521502a', '100002785406', 'Section 1 Posting - Volunteer Opportunity: After School Community Learning Programme Are you interested in supporting young learners while gaining useful experience? Volunteers are invited to join the After School Community Learning Programme, which supports students aged 8–12 as they explore specialised subjects in a safe and welcoming environment. Before beginning, volunteers attend an introductory session where they learn about programme routines, available materials, safety procedures, and expectations from experienced staff. This session helps volunteers understand how lessons are organised and what support is provided so they feel prepared. After the session, volunteers select their preferred subject and arrange their schedule through a form. All necessary supplies are provided. 2 The After School Community Learning Programme is ideal for volunteers who want to develop leadership and communication skills while working directly with children. Another initiative, the School Peer Observation Programme, takes a different approach. In that programme, participants attend lessons, complete observation checklists, and discuss teaching strategies during meetings to reflect on their experience, but they do not usually interact with students. In contrast, the After School Community Learning Programme offers an active teaching environment. Volunteers support small groups, guide students through learning tasks, and help them practise study routines during scheduled sessions. They also encourage focus and positive behaviour, contributing to an organised and supportive space. These regular interactions build students’ confidence and allow volunteers to contribute meaningfully to their community, which many previous volunteers have found rewarding. <p data-ccp-props="{&quot;335551550&quot;:1,&quot;335551620&quot;:1,&quot;335559683&quot;:0,&quot;335562764&quot;:2,&quot;335562765&quot;:1,&quot;335562766&quot;:4,&quot;335562767&quot;:0', 'Reading comprehension', 'Synthesising and critically engaging with text', 'D1', 1, 'active'),
  ('d3f03942-4feb-5b88-ac22-238176361cd4', '3385d4a5-b4c2-5331-a7a9-53a03f3f4869', '2ee55359-b5ce-5fa2-8710-cb048521502a', '100002785409', 'Section 1 Posting - Volunteer Opportunity: After School Community Learning Programme Are you interested in supporting young learners while gaining useful experience? Volunteers are invited to join the After School Community Learning Programme, which supports students aged 8–12 as they explore specialised subjects in a safe and welcoming environment. Before beginning, volunteers attend an introductory session where they learn about programme routines, available materials, safety procedures, and expectations from experienced staff. This session helps volunteers understand how lessons are organised and what support is provided so they feel prepared. After the session, volunteers select their preferred subject and arrange their schedule through a form. All necessary supplies are provided. 2 The After School Community Learning Programme is ideal for volunteers who want to develop leadership and communication skills while working directly with children. Another initiative, the School Peer Observation Programme, takes a different approach. In that programme, participants attend lessons, complete observation checklists, and discuss teaching strategies during meetings to reflect on their experience, but they do not usually interact with students. In contrast, the After School Community Learning Programme offers an active teaching environment. Volunteers support small groups, guide students through learning tasks, and help them practise study routines during scheduled sessions. They also encourage focus and positive behaviour, contributing to an organised and supportive space. These regular interactions build students’ confidence and allow volunteers to contribute meaningfully to their community, which many previous volunteers have found rewarding. <p data-ccp-props="{&quot;335551550&quot;:1,&quot;335551620&quot;:1,&quot;335559683&quot;:0,&quot;335562764&quot;:2,&quot;335562765&quot;:1,&quot;335562766&quot;:4,&quot;335562767&quot;:0', 'Reading comprehension', 'Synthesising and critically engaging with text', 'D3', 1, 'active'),
  ('c946f26c-227c-541f-a43e-6368f2f9b98a', '3385d4a5-b4c2-5331-a7a9-53a03f3f4869', '2ee55359-b5ce-5fa2-8710-cb048521502a', '100002785504', 'Section 1 Short story: Migration Through a Young Man’s Eyes Kareem learned early to notice backgrounds rather than destinations. The colour of walls, the sound of streets at night, the way light shone through unfamiliar windows. These were what changed each season his family moved for work. Adults would always call the moves temporary, but Kareem stopped believing that word. He became used to packing quickly and carefully, keeping formal documents flat and other small objects safe, knowing they could impact important life outcomes. When he was able to attend government schools in the villages they passed through, he watched friendships become solid around him while his own remained unformed. Teachers spoke confidently about students setting goals for future years, yet Kareem measured time in days. 2 Responsibility had entered Kareem’s life quietly, without permission, even when he was a young boy. He translated instructions for his parents, calculated wages that never matched the costs of feeding a family and learned to read the silence of supervisors in the fields where he and his parents worked. Throughout his teenage years, his days followed a strict rhythm – working before sunrise, studying during the day, chores until late at night – leaving little space for rest or dreaming. Yet a quiet doubt followed him. He realised that he was enduring without choosing, moving forward because stopping felt dangerous rather than because the path felt right. He became unsettled: was perseverance, or pushing through despite challenges, still admirable if it had become automatic, leaving no space for change? This is what got him and his family through the most difficult moments, after all. <td tabindex="0" data-celllook="0" rowspan="1" co', 'Reading comprehension', 'Understanding meaning', 'D2', 1, 'active'),
  ('3c2318c5-0e65-546e-b62f-e55046de83da', '3385d4a5-b4c2-5331-a7a9-53a03f3f4869', '2ee55359-b5ce-5fa2-8710-cb048521502a', '100002785509', 'Section 1 Short story: Migration Through a Young Man’s Eyes Kareem learned early to notice backgrounds rather than destinations. The colour of walls, the sound of streets at night, the way light shone through unfamiliar windows. These were what changed each season his family moved for work. Adults would always call the moves temporary, but Kareem stopped believing that word. He became used to packing quickly and carefully, keeping formal documents flat and other small objects safe, knowing they could impact important life outcomes. When he was able to attend government schools in the villages they passed through, he watched friendships become solid around him while his own remained unformed. Teachers spoke confidently about students setting goals for future years, yet Kareem measured time in days. 2 Responsibility had entered Kareem’s life quietly, without permission, even when he was a young boy. He translated instructions for his parents, calculated wages that never matched the costs of feeding a family and learned to read the silence of supervisors in the fields where he and his parents worked. Throughout his teenage years, his days followed a strict rhythm – working before sunrise, studying during the day, chores until late at night – leaving little space for rest or dreaming. Yet a quiet doubt followed him. He realised that he was enduring without choosing, moving forward because stopping felt dangerous rather than because the path felt right. He became unsettled: was perseverance, or pushing through despite challenges, still admirable if it had become automatic, leaving no space for change? This is what got him and his family through the most difficult moments, after all. <p data-ccp-props="{&quot;335551550&quot;:2,&quot;335551620&quot;:2,&quot;335559683&quot;:0,&quot;335562764&quot;:4,&quot;33556276', 'Reading comprehension', 'Evaluating meaning', 'D3', 1, 'active'),
